title: set of gears for collaborative extruder

description.text:
if you want more push and your motor just cannot catch up with your desires, you need to throw lower gear.
now you have choice handy. thanks to ring nut gears you can use also 6,5,4 and 3 toothed small gear. trick is to position the nut very precisely (it should be melted hot with i.e. soldering iron ) with 52:6 , threaded hobbed bolt and 1/16 microstepping my esteps are 1270 now (vs 630 while used 44:10 gears) that gives decent push and i can extrude ABS @ 200C. enjoy. edit: new files for less wobble gears.
they use smaller nut , and allow positioning top of motor shaft inside the gear. I do recommend glueining the nut in place with ABS juice and also using allen head locknut - also glued after locking the shaft . for 52:4 gear ratio my Esteps (provided just for reference) are 1820.
Note that with such ratio max retract speed might be a problem - in my setup it can be 12mm/s max - anything above causes missed steps and stringing.

description.text:
This is a E3D V6 mount for a K8200. This mount is compatible with the original extruder and can hold two fan shrouds. There are also probe holders available on thingyverse that will fit this mount.

The halves screw together around the E3Dv6 heatsink. The bottom two screws are countersunk into the part and the top two also mount the E3D fan. It is mounted this way because the longest M3 nuts i could find were 30mm long, longer bolts would save some hastle. I also had to cut away part of the E3D fan so that my bolts would reach the nuts. update 7/11/17: Added "v2" freecad file which adds the nut knob, same sort of deal as the screw knob but for an external hex bolt 10mm flat to flat.

title: $5 WiFi Light Switch: In Wall Sonoff Light Switch Box

description.text:
This is a box for a Sonoff Basic that mounts inside existing light switch housing.

This is a remix of the 530_Projects DIY In-Wall Sonoff Light Switch. His version uses an additional circuit board to trigger GPIO pins on the Sonoff. This version is only 3d printed.

This version requires no other parts other than what is printed. It uses a diving board mechanism to actuate the button on the Sonoff when the light switch it flipped. Because of this, it functions like a 3-way switch, cycling the relay regardless of previous position of the switch actuator.

Instructions:
1)Print 1 of each file. 10% infill no supports for the case_back, case_front, and button_board. The switch_actuator requires supports and should be printed at 25% or greater infill. Print the button_board with the cup facing up for best results.
2) Assembly: there is a small slot in the case_back where the button_board end gets inserted with the small cup facing the back, furthest from the wall, see picture (it secures the end of the button), it is intentionally a tight fit, so you may have to file it a little to get it to work. Next, remove the Sonoff from its factory casing and slide it into the case_back with the notched end first. Lift the button_board to make sure it slides all the way in and that the cup on the button_board is surrounding the top of the button. Place the switch_actuator into the case_front. The hyperbolic tab on the back of the actuator will push the button_board up and down. Wire the Sonoff and then attach the front of the case to the back.

MAKE SURE THE BUTTON IS NOT PRESSED WHEN YOU TURN ON POWER TO THE SONOFF (it will go into flash mode).

I am running Tasmota on my Sonoffs which is available here: https://github.com/arendst/Sonoff-Tasmota

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Wago 222 terminal connectors – and their clear plastic 221 siblings – are great for interconnecting solid, stranded and fine-stranded wires of varying gauges. Plus there’s no screws to mess with, just lift the lever fully, insert wire(s) and close the lever. Done.

I used them in my ‘Quick-Detach LACK-top 12V Power Connector’ (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2614691) for power distribution to whatever I might wire into my enclosure.

This Thing is a cable harness and easy slide-off cover for the 5-conductor Wago 222 terminal blocks. There’s room for two in there – i.e. one for positive and one for negative power distribution.

Materials List

  • 2 – Wago 222 terminal connectors
  • 2 – M5 screws for the harness (M6 would work as well with a little ‘convincing’)
  • 1 – M6 screw for the notch in the slide-off cover (preferably with a big flanged button head)

Note Wago do sell a more elaborate “mounting carrier” for their 222s if you don’t feel like printing one. There’s also other Wago holders on Thingiverse without covers if you don’t mind looking at wires.

title: Amiibo Stand System - No Connectors
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Edit 11/17/2017: I can't believe I didn't mention this sooner! If you're into the idea of the Amiibo stand system WITH connectors, I have a new Thing posted you'll want to check out:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2629107

I have a lot of Amiibo, and I think it's safe to say that they end up taking over if you let them.

So I went and did a search on the Internet, and found this fantastic guide to making an Amiibo stand out of wood:

https://imgur.com/gallery/P68cT

I took the general design, tweaked the sizes, and made this thing:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2613221

It was perfect, ready to go, and it even had space at the top for the larger Amiibo!

Sadly, it wouldn't print on my FFCP 2016, because it was huge!

So I did what any self-respecting designer and engineer would do: I brainstormed.

First, I did a search, and found that a lot of folks have Amiibo holders, but they're generally flat, and not a stand like this. I like the multi-level stands. But how could I print multi-level stands, if the maximum my printer would allow is 4x3? That's too small.

Then the answer came to me: modularization.

I decided that all I really needed were building blocks, and I could then stick them together however I wanted! Plus, printing a single module takes (on my printer) anywhere from 3 hours for the small one, to ten hours for the tall one. I don't like prints that have to run overnight or for multiple days. So can you imagine how long it would take to print a whole stand all at once? Simplify3D claims it would take over 24 hours.

So the module system is perfect! You can print as many of the low, medium and high platforms as you'd like, stick them together using PLA-friendly double-sided tape, you could stick them together at the bottom using something like Con-Tact paper:

http://contactbrand.com/

Or if you wanted to be extra bold, you could use Cyanoacrylate (Super Glue) for that never-coming-apart-ever bond:

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyanoacrylate

This is the first iteration, and I think some folks will enjoy this project as it is. It's done, ready to download and use however you'd like to use it. If you make something with this, or remix it, please let me know, and share a Make or Remix here.

If you'd like different heights, sizes, margins, just let me know. I've designed these in Fusion 360 using 100% parameterization, so changing a specific diameter and posting a special item would be trivial. If you want to sketch something out, you can do a Make here, or leave comments with links to Imgur. I'm fairly responsive.

The next version is going to be a little more fun, though. I sketched out the system on my iPad, and these building blocks were the first stage. I wanted to make sure I could design something modular, that would print well. I've done that.

I believe the next version is going to have pins-and-holes, with different hole placements, so you can have all the varying hole placements you should need/want. Front, middle, back, left, center, right. That way, if you want to have low, medium, high like in the standard stand I shared earlier, you will be able to arrange them in that way. But if you wanted to do something like low, medium, low, high or something, I'll have a version for each, so it can sit in the front, middle or back, whether low, medium or high.

That's going to take a little more planning, but it's on the horizon.

Questions, comments? I love to hear them!

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

No

Resolution:

Medium

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I tried printing these at a lower infill other than 30%, and they came out terrible. Really bad. That's not to say with the right printer, leveling, filament, settings, and patience, you couldn't print this perfectly at 10% or something, but I'd say 30% is a nice, solid (but not too solid) balance. If you find a better way to print this lighter, let me know.

This iteration doesn't need supports. I suspect the next version with the holes in the sides will probably need supports inside, but those would be easy to pull out. Plus, the support remnants will make a nice friction base for the connecting rods. We'll see!

Easy Cleanup

You shouldn't need to do much more than just the standard clean-up for a print.

As a reminder, darker colors hide shadows and lines, and lighter colors emphasize shadows and lines. So if you want to make the seams "disappear" a little, print in a darker color, like black. If you don't mind the seams, go ahead and print in whatever color you'd like.

You may want to put "mickey mouse ears" in the corners of the print, if you experience curling in the corners. At least one of my prints had a little curling, but that was only in one corner, so I just hid it in the back. Easy!

Fusion 360 and Simplify3D

This is a very basic design: parameters for the size of the cube, including heights, using the Fibonacci sequence/Golden Ratio for the ultimate in visual aesthetics. (It's better than guessing!) I actually had a spreadsheet to come up with the heights, and the ratio from height to size. I gave these a little extra margin around the Amiibo hole, so you have extra space for medium-sized Amiibo. If you need more space for a large Amiibo, try elevating above using the tall, as shown with Bowser in the photo.

I love parametric design, and although it takes a little longer to set things up, it pays off in the end. Fusion 360 is incredible. They have a few things to work out, but I'm hoping, over time, some of my minor concerns will be fixed.

Simplify3D is incredible, and slices up my prints so optimally. And I send those prints off to my printer using the Toshiba FlashAir card. I think I'm using the W03, but I heard there's a W04 out now. I wonder if it's more awesome?

title: CNC pen / sharpie holder for plotter

description.text:
Use your CNC router as a plotter!
This was 100% inspired by TadasM https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1847711
However I wanted to make it easy printable without any supports, imperial instead of metric and working with sharpie so I created my very own version from scratch. I love the concept where the spring is incorporated in the design! (And it works!)
This uses 1/4" 4" screw from home depot that has only small thread length at the end - just cut out the thread and you have a perfect 1/4" shaft of 3 1/4 length for this project.
All other screws are 8-32 - the 2b threads are perfectly realized in the stl, no need to retap.

All dimensions are very precisely set; the top collar fits very very tightly and stays even without the screw and the bottom collars slide freely but without any play on the shaft. The screw holes all have 8-32 thread realized.
The hole fits the standard sharpie and the double sided sharpies.
I'll post more pics of it actually working on the CNC.

No

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

Notes:

Prints without support. I used 3 outline shells for extra rigidity and 4 top and bottom full layers. Printed in white PLA+ which does have feel of UHMW. Try it - it is very durable and beats normal PLA, ABS or nylon imho.. If you are not sure your printer can make the big sharpie hole without support, stick some in the middle. (but most well tuned printers should be fine)
Orientation is how you see it here, this ensures the perfect realization of 8-32 threads which are in 2b class and the screw goes in and out perfectly.
It is great when you just design a thing and it prints and it is exactly as you wanted!

title: New and Improved Handle For Mjolnir

description.text:
Handle pieces 2.0A and 2.0B, as well as HandleHead2.0B, all need to be printed with 100% infill.

I have recreated the handle for Mjolnir, for a much cleaner appearance when using heat shrink tubing for the handle wrap. All pieces are designed to fit around a section of PVC tubing, 3/4 inches in size. The outer diameter of the PVC is barely over 1 inch. 1.052 to be exact.

I have used a dual walled, adhesive lined heat shrink tubing, for the "leather" wrap of the handle. When using this technique, you must print the handle piece and slide it over the PVC tubing first! The heat and lack of support will just allow the heat shrink to just crumble your piece if not.

For the Pommel pieces, after wrapping, some material will need to be removed to allow everything to fit snug together. It's super easy. Just reference the pictures.

The HeadBodyB2.0 piece has been modified to accept the 3/4in PVC tubing.

1 1/2 inch to 2 inch heat shrink tubing is required.

The final length of PVC tubing needed is 17inches.

11-5-17 Just added HeadBodyB2.0B and HeadCapScroll2.0. These 2 pieces help lock everything together a little better. Just run the PVC all the way through the HeadBody piece and the Cap piece will seat inside the PVC tube, locking everyting in. I haven't printed these yet, but they should work. Holla at me if there's problems.

11-7-17 HeadCapScroll2.0 was removed because I was getting poor results with the print orientation. I will re-work it and try again. I'll repost the updated file when fixed.
11-12-17 HeadCapScroll2.0 was added back. Just changed print orientation. You have to use support to print obviously. When I printed it the original way, with the lettering on the print surface, it wasn't consistently adhering all of the letters, resulting in a big mess. You may have different results. In the end I wonder if it's even worth it or even needed?

Also, when assembling the handle, you will have small gaps here and there. If you don't want the white PVC showing through, order BLACK PVC. If you just merely paint the white PVC black you will have a hard time sliding the handle pieces over the PVC because the tolerances are so tight. The gaps are small and hardly noticeable.

11-25-17 Update I just realized that HandleHead2.0B piece was the wrong orientation. It has been fixed so that the handle lines up in the right now.

description.text:
This is third iteration of a camera for time-lapse based on a Raspberry-pi.

The base is made of a framework of 9x9mm oak sticks which provide a good rigidity. The bottom part of the base contains 2 places for magnets to fix the camera on metallic surfaces like the roof of the car. There is also room for a nut to mount the camera on a photo-tripod. You will need a 1/2" nut, not that easy to find in Europe.

Above this is a place for a USB-power bank. I took the largest available 44000mAH from Amazon. It hold 24h for the time-lapse which is comfortable

Then is the stage for the Raspberry Pi. Initially it was a RPi v2 with a wifi dongle but it has been upgraded to a RPi v3 at the second iteration. It is under-clocked for more battery lifetime. A usb stick is used for photo storage. On the Raspberry pi board is mounted a PWM controller for the servo-motors and a RTC clock. Everything is interfaced in I2C

On the top of the base is the servo-motor for panoramic movement.

For the movement:
There is a panorama servo-motor which provides a rotation to the right or to the left, a DSS-M15S from DFRobot with a rotation over 270° on the top of the base. The tilt movement (up and down) is provided by a MG92s from TowerPro, but cheaper SG90 and MG90 also fit.
You will need in addition a 608 ball-bearing facing the tilt-servo for ensuring a proper movement of the head.

For the camera:
I use a raspberry-pi camera (version 1) with a CS-mount a 4mm lens.
http://www.uctronics.com/ov5647-camera-board-w-cs-mount-lens-fully-compatible-with-raspberry-pi.html

Additional feature: there is room for a MMA8451 accelerator (from Adafruit) to measure the orientation of the photography in the head of the camera.
https://learn.adafruit.com/adafruit-mma8451-accelerometer-breakout/overview
This information is important for assembling the time-lapse video to keep the horizon at the horizontal :)

First iteration: mainly commercial stuff + head

It had a OV5647 module with CS mount and lens. The quality of the photo was OK but the motors was not shaking all the time (and noisy).

to make this video:

Second iteration: Better camera ... or not

The second iteration had already the same "wooden" base which is compact and reliable.

The camera head was based on a Raspberry-pi camera version 2 with 8 megapixel. The stock lens has been removed to mount a M12 wide angle lens (f'=2.8mm). I did not manage to get a good quality image. The accelerometer was reliable to "rotate" the images in post-treatement. The raspberry-pi is also able to perform accumulation of frames to reach "long" exposure time and correct for the flatfield effect due to the change of lens.

The third iteration is simply the base of v2 and the camera of v1.

First time-lapse camera on the top of the camper Camera version 2 with the M12 lens and the 8Mpix sensor Third iteration: Calibration of the lens on a grid of points
Time-lapse photography This camera allows to make accelerated movie of landscapes like sunset, ...

description.text:
This is a kid sized "prop" Trollhunters Sword in three sections to print on 210x210 print beds.

My 5 year old nephew wanted to be Trollhunter for Halloween and I had no idea what he was talking about but after looking at some photos and the basic foam suggestions out there I figured I could make him something a bit better. Its far from perfect and was a one off, so I apologize for any inaccuracies, I'm not a cosplayer.

Using the Trollhunter Sword by Jockelill as a basic outline I scaled it WAY up, cut it in half and then added the sword details.

This is built with an interior void to accommodate 5 blue LEDs inside per side along with a 2 x AA battery pack, as seen in the terrible photos on my messy workbench (sorry).
I just cut a section of thin white plastic (from my wife's tupperware lids so don't tell her) which I placed inside over the openings to make the lighting more diffuse, you could likely print something to form. I may have gotten carried away with the number of LEDs as its kind of blinding.

Basically I printed this in PVC, printing two of each sword section and then using acetone and an old soldering iron to bond the three sections of each side together on the inside face. I used the acetone to do an initial bonding of the sections together and used the old soldering iron to pull material together from section to section to make a stronger bond.

Someone with more skills than me can likely come up with a better mechanical method to attach everything together. If you're interested just let me know and I can send you the sketchup file.

I drilled small holes from one side into the other and counter sunk them to fit self tapping plastic screws which hold the two halves together.

I also made an amulet which you can put LEDs in which I will post separately.

description.text: This is a caliper which is derived from several others here and elsewhere, but not enough from any single one that I felt like it qualified as a derivitive of any one in particular.  It is made on a laser cutter and gives readings accurate to 0.05 mm or 1/128 inch.  The actual accuracy will depend on the fit of the parts you make.

Cut the parts as shown. I included one file with everything (full) or if you need the cutting and marking actions separate, there are separate files for those. There are three layers to the finished caliper. The part "3" is on the bottom and holds the sliding part together. Part "2A" is a bit wider than part "1A", so it keeps everything from falling apart (see detail photo). Parts "2B" and "2C" and a bit narrower than "1B" and "1C" to accommodate the width of "2A". Note that part "3" actually sits upside down - flip it over from the orientation as it is cut. This was done to fit the parts into a smaller area and waste less material when cutting.
The example in the photos was made with laser engraving material which has a white body and an overcoat of black plastic. The laser engraving cuts away the black and leaves the white showing. Depending on the material you use, you might want to use double-sided tape between parts "1A" and "2A". Just be sure not to let the tape get close enough to the edge that it interferes with the operation of the sliding piece.
The holes are sized for US size 6-32 screws to hold everything together.

title: Luzbot Taz 4/5 Bed Leveler
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
edit 11/25/17 if you are interested in BuildTak's FlexPlate system, take a look at my additional mod I've posted here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2669280

I'm very pleased with how this mod turned out. It is quite simple and can completely be reverted if you so choose. I really can't believe I didn't think to do this sooner, but I'm trying to buy as much life out of my Taz 4 as possible and the only area I haven't upgraded is the bed leveling.

The dial is a remix of the model I've linked to and both the bottom and top (aka 'fingers') models are remixes of the originals. The bed 'fingers' are longer to better hold the glass in place, but do not interfere with the home position (it's a bit close, but it doesn't touch the hotend). The bottom has been remixed to better slide up and down inverted bolts.

Parts needed:
(8) 20mm m3 bolts (https://www.mcmaster.com/mv1509661997/#catalog/91290A123)
(4) 25mm m3 bolts (https://www.mcmaster.com/mv1509661997/#catalog/91290A125)
(4) m3 heat inserts (https://www.mcmaster.com/mv1509661997/#catalog/94180A331)
(8) springs (https://www.homedepot.com/p/Everbilt-Spring-Assortment-Kit-84-Pack-13554/203133714)

I am honestly unsure which springs I used, as I didn't have any and bought two variety packs from Home Depot. They are slightly shorter than the existing springs used to level the bed. They are also not as strong as the existing springs, but fairly stiff. It requires two variety packs, but you get a lot more springs for the price of a small bag from McMaster.

Step 1 - print (4) of each of the three models
Step 2 - insert the heat inserts into each of the dials
Step 3 - heat press the 25mm bolts into the Bed Leveler 'fingers'

  • trick - I used a heat insert to make the hole, removed it, then inserted the bolt with heat

Step 4 - disassemble the bed and remove it and the stock corner parts
Step 5 - Use a drill to slightly expand the unused, pre-drilled hole in each corner enough to allow the m3 bolt to freely pass through it
Step 6 - Screw the (8) 20mm bolts in from the bottom (two in each corner) of the originally used holes so that the threads face up
Step 7 - place the new springs over each of the inverted screws
Step 8 - place the bottom bed leveler part of the bed leveler onto each corner
Step 9 - place the glass bed back into position
Step 10 - place the original springs in between the bottom bed leveler part and the corner holes
Step 11 - put the bed leveler 'finger' in the corner hole of the bottom bed leveler part, from the top, through the original spring, and the previously drilled expanded hole in each corner
Step 12 - compress the bed leveler 'finger' and screw the dial in from below
Step 13 - relevel the bed

title: 3dTouch Sensor Mount Geeetech I3 Pro C(B) mounting
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Update: see .PDF for more information. Thingiverse was not saving my update correctly.
If you use this, please share a picture of it. Thanks.

Ok, here is the long awaited 3Dtouch update to my auto-level post. Not really a re-mix. So many projects kept me from finishing this before now. Including upgrading my printer with a metal bed (leveling problems). But this new upgrade works well.

Please refer back to my original post ‘Geeetech i3 Pro C inductive sensor mount by JD_Printing, published Sep 3, 2016’ for Marlin printer setting. Take note of probing points! And how to calculate them. I will only talk about the changes and how to calibrate the probe here.

I followed the 3dtouch auto leveling senor user manual for modifying my GT2560 board. Good instructions for the most part and I had no problem hooking up the sensor. Just a note; go by wire color not the position in the sensor plug!

I was not sure of the height needed for the probe so I made this one adjustable. It does require a little bit of filing and/or sanding to get a smooth movement. But a little stiffness is good when adjusting.

Printer:

geeetech Prusa I3 Pro C

Supports:

No
filing or sanding needed to move smoothly. Don't need to overdo it.
The original was drawn in Freecad. This has been redone with Fusion360. A much more powerful and easier to use program. And did I mention FREE!

Problems:
Problem 1: First note; I was not able to compile with the newest Arduino IDE software (ver 1.8.5) Didn’t work! Kept giving me syntax errors. I finally had to removed the new version and reinstall version 1.0.6. Old version worked perfectly – no syntax errors. The old version is still available on Arduino site.
Problem 2: testing:
My probe only goes up and down twice, not the 3 times the manual says. (maybe I have an older 3dtouch? I did buy it a long time ago).
The probe was not responding to commands. Yea, dummy me! I was so careful to keep the wire color straight. Somehow I reversed the plug on the sensor. Lucky for me the power pin is the center and no damage was done. So when I say watch the wire colors, I know what I am saying! Works fine now.

Now comes the Marlin firmware settings. (see Calibration section. This is really part of calibration). I had to change the probe_offset _range as it was not allowing me to change it to -1.55. kept saying it was out of range. Someone on the Geeetech forum suggested changing to min -20 max 20. This did the trick
“#define CUSTOM_M_CODES
“#ifdef CUSTOM_M_CODES
“ #define CUSTOM_M_CODE_SET_Z_PROBE_OFFSET 851
“ #define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_RANGE_MIN -20 // -15
“ #define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_RANGE_MAX 20 // -5 ;****
“#endif”

The Geeetech manual I downloaded from the Geeetech site has no information on calibration (height), but the WIKI site does. I have copied it from https://www.geeetech.com/wiki/index.php/3DTouch_Auto_Leveling_Sensor and added my corrections here. My notes start with (“.

These instructions are written to explain how to calibrate using a computer connected through the USB port to your printer. This process also assumes that the EEPROM has been enabled in Marlin.
From the command window of Repetier Host or Simplify3D etc enter the following:
M851 ; note the number
M851 Z0 ; set the offset to zero
G28
G1 Z0
The LCD display should show Z = 0
(“ everything worked great to here. Then…)
From the display go to the Menu then Prepare/Move axis/0.1mm/Move Z
(“ on my printer I can not drive below 0 on the Z axis. Use G92 Z10. Sets Z axis to 10. Then you can move lower. Just subtract final number from 10 to get setting)
Now move the Z axis slowly down until the nozzle is the right distance from the build plate (folded piece of paper or thin card).
*Note the Z axis value on the display it should be something like -1.5

(“ example: Z axis on mine read 8.9. Now calculate 10 – 8.9 = 1.1 use -1.1)
M851 Z-1.5 ; to set the offset you got in the previous step. (*** this sets the Z offset to -1.5)
M500 ; Stores the values in EEPROM so that it is not reset when you power the printer off and on.
Now you are ready to print.

description.text: Famous name for scramblers

FTC robotics has many cables that go to sensors, batteries, servo motors, DC motors, etc. The problem is that these various components can move or vibrate putting stress on the connective to the REV module.

We designed a simple cable strain relief part that sits on top of the REV module (can even be screwed into the REV module and it's Actobotix holder. Once there, cables can be be plugged into the REV module and then zip tied to the cable strain holder. This should eliminate cables from becoming detached or cables straining the REV module connections.

It's a big part

FTC Robotics cable problems We have historically had problems in FTC robotics with cables coming loose, cables warping electronics modules and other problems. In the past cable strain relief had been ad hoc and typically involved zip tying cables to acrobatics structural elements. But previously there were a lot more electronics modules involved. With the REV module all the electronics control modules were centralized into one package with dozen's of cable connections coming in/out. So having a cable strain relief for the REV module could solve many problems with one part.

3D parts and FTC robotics I really don't know what to put here. It helps to have a 3D printer, we used Lulbotz Mini for printing this part but any good 3D printer should suffice. The part is big (137mmX97mmX33mm), some 3D printers may be unable to print it out, so check with your printer specifications to see if it will work. The application used to design it was Autodesk Fusion 360 (see: https://www.autodesk.com/products/fusion-360/overview). This is available free for any academic person or affiliated coaches/teachers/professors. I highly recommend this software for it's tutorials and ease of use. It's a bit daunting at first but watch some of the tutorials and give it a try. It's really easy once you understand what tools are available and what the various screen icons mean. If you want to prefer to use a more open source design tool, give SolveSpace a try (See http://solvespace.com/index.pl). It's not as powerful as Fusion 360 but it's completely open sourced and last I looked support was excellent. Here too, you need to check out the written and video tutorials before I would start using the software. The nice thing about most FTC parts (Actobotics) and electronics (REV) modules is that the part structural (3D models) designs are often available and can be downloaded for free. Look under the Resources Tab for Actobotics structural parts and there you will find the downloads. With these downloads you can (using Fusion 360) measure any characteristic you have to match up to (such as hole positions, REV module heights, etc.). And you can even take these models and 3D print a part that looks exactly like the mechanical design. So I took the REV module, measured the screw distances, screw hole sizes, REV module height, width, & depth and designed my part to fit it's exact measurements. Without Fusion 360, it's a question of accurate measurement of the part to be matched. This can sometimes take a few part prints to get right but over time, you get better (more precise) at measuring distances from actual parts. There are plenty of other 3D parts that can be printed. We find the phone holder wings occasionally break off and this is a challenge part to reproduce (no design available online). But it can be done and we have done it and will upload someday. Other parts include gripper assemblies to scale the gripper up or down to use for different size objects. Slider assemblies that can be used to tailor a slider-servo mechanism to better mount to Actobotics and acrobotics to other part connections/fasteners. Actobotics has a unique form factor, screw hole pattern, which varies depending on the pattern repetitions and screw position. Using other electronics (such as Modern Robotics) often requires different mounting adjusters to correctly fasten these to acrobatics parts. We have done some of this and will be uploading parts shortly that match these. As a stundent lesson plan, I would start with simple parts with limited surface geometry and maybe just hole registration (such as mounting REV module or Modern Robotics modules to Actobotics structural parts. Move onto gripper/slider assembly modification parts and maybe in the end the cable strain assembly (just be cause it's most involved). But this is just our part history. I truly believe you can almost 3D print your whole robot except for the electronics and cables if you wanted to and that would be a great project

title: 9004 Bulb Lock Ring for Ford Trucks (Prob other Makes/Models)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
UPDATE!!! Just to give the user a choice, I added the V3 files. V3 has a shorter flex clip than V2. That is the only difference. V2 is damn near unbreakable, V3 can break but ABS/Acetone is the cure even after/while the bulb is installed.

SO you wanted to upgrade your old truck/car headlights because they're dim and even though you shined them up and got em mostly crystal clear... The light was just not up to par.

SO you decided you'd buy yourself some fancy LED lights cuz they're brighter and it can't be that hard to do this upgrade right?.....

Your first mistake was using the word upgrade and easy when talking about your older vehicle. Haven't you learned this by now?????

Well I'm here to help you with that upgrade! I have an 87 Ford Bronco with the classic 9004 headlight bulbs which are VERY common on older and still even some new vehicles. In many situations that lock ring is the same since the fit is universal and there wasn't any need to make it fancy. So while this is for my Bronco, it'll work on any F-X50 from 87 to 92, Econolines of the same year/engine series, and it looked like Dodge uses the same ring too. Probably plenty of other manufacturers/models that use this as well.

The existing lock rings do not work because they are so deep and it doesn't allow the wire to work in the space. You can modify it but I don't know how easy it is to replace one and older vehicles are becoming scarce in the junkyards. I can only find one F-150 in my year out of the whole series in any junkyard in the valley right now...

That's why I decided to design my own and try to address the issues I had with the "simple" install.
First is the locking nubs are fixed. I made them so they will have a bit of flex but should remain sturdy. If you snap one, then ABS/Acetone glue to the rescue! Honestly not a bad idea to just coat it anyways to ensure it's VERY solid but it already is VERY solid :) I also angled the nubs on the side that contact the bulb body first to give a bit easier slip fit on. With mine it is a bit rough but it's a really tight tolerance and if it's just a bit larger it will not lock the bulb in. So if you install these, you'll find out quick you're gonna still use a bit of force to get them in but holding the bulb body around the rubber gasket, NOT the bulb itself, lining the new lock ring up just right, and then you can pop it in. It won't be as bad as it sounds, but if the body is not perfectly aligned to the ring, it will be significantly more difficult if not impossible as the angle increases. Be patient, steady, and you'll get it in :D

The next issue and the biggest is the wire. These are Hikari but they all appear to have the same body/build and since they are a universal fit, you can be pretty sure it's consistent.
The body of the LED bulb is larger due to them adding in fans so it's impossible to get the bulb through the original lock ring because of the seating ring protrusion unless you sand this all down a lot.
So I made the seating ring stick out less but still provide a seat. I also included 3 spaces where it does not protrude at all giving a LIL extra clearance for that wire.

The last thing I addressed was when the wire is fully through, it will be pinched the rest of it's life if you kept the original full body and height of the lock ring. I kept the height but I cut out 3 large slots for the wire to hang with less stress.

I really hope this helps someone out giving someone the option to turn those old dangerous night driving headlights that you almost might as well just leave off since they don't do much anyways, into a classic look with modern/safe lighting!
I should also say because there is no such thing as up with this part i.e. it doesn't have just one way it goes on, you should have plenty of adjustability to get the LEDs aligned properly because YES, the 9004 and most LED lamps do require alignment. What does that mean? It means make sure the covered side of the LED is pointed to the sky unless you like blinding people because you're a jerk ;)

This is a 3D mini-MakerBot replica.
Included is a family portrait with the proud parent.
The Google SketchUp file contains the parts at both full size and scaled to 0.2 to fit the MakerBot print platform.

The three components are printed separately to avoid undoable overhangs. The parts have notches so that they stay centered.
This also allowed me to print the body of the mini-maker blue and the plastruder white.
I simulated the heater / nozzle with a short piece of a round toothpick pushed into the 2mm square hole printed into the bottom of the insulator barrel. (Yes: I pushed a round peg into a square hole)
Note the counter sunk holes and bolts thru the build platform to give a larger usable build area. This also eliminates the risk of smashing the nozzle into the socket heads and breaking something in the plastruder.

Alligator Clip to 4mm Banana Terminals

This was designed to allow me to connect a foam cutter to a battery charger. I realised that connecting a car power plug would allow me to easily connect my lipo charger to the car without messing around with the car battery.

Versions

Version Module Description
Alligator Clips to Terminals Base_Clip(); Convert alligator clips to 4mm plugs, terminals.
Car Power Socket to Terminals or Alligator Clips Case_Top_Entry(); Case_Bot(); Convert a car power socket to alligator clips or 4mm plugs, terminal

You will need a car power plug e.g. Car Lighter Power Plug. Better still cannibalise something.

Printing

You will need Terminal.scad in your OpenSCAD Library folder or Car Power Socket folder.

These need to take some knocks, 3 shells and 30% or greater fill for strength.
Fit the terminals to the top and then glue the base to the top.

description.text:
Summary

An example of 3D model generated with my Gugulele OnShape script…

  • Decorative headless gourd shaped design
  • Concert ukulele scale length
  • Double rectangular through-body spine
  • Single oval off center sound hole
  • 'T' Bracing
  • Tail-end placement of tuners
  • 4 pieces using M1.6 socket head screws

I designed this for smaller printer that can print about 200mm x 200mm x 300mm (Z axis). I have yet to print this particular model so let me know if you have succeeded in printing one.

Third Party Parts:

  • 2x Spine/rods e.g. http://www.acpsales.com/.125-x-.325-Rectangular-Rod.html or https://dragonplate.com/ecart/product.asp?pID=749&cID=20
    • get a 24" long and cut it down to size, can't remember exactly...
    • if you don't use a rod, the neck will bow under string tension
  • Gotoh UPT-UBB-B Tuners e.g. http://www.theukulelesite.com/gotoh-upt-tuner-upgrade.html
    • its possible to use other tuners, be creative!
  • 11x Long Screws (M1.6x10) for fretboard long holes e.g. https://www.amazon.com/M1-6x10mm-Stainless-Socket-Screws-100pcs/dp/B011BNUXNI
    • can't remember how many you need, just buy a bag of 100

You may need to glue the parts together! The screws are there to provide alignment and help hold parts together while waiting for the glue to cure...

description.text:
This electrical box and switch mount is designed to work with my stock power supply mount linked below. I designed the lid to mount with small screws or ~3mm bolts from the back. Printing Instructions: Print the conduit with "build plate only" supports. The box and lid print with normal supports in given orientations.

11-5-17 Rounded edges. Rotated STL's for correct printing positions. Added wedges to minimise supports on the box.
11-6-17 Final updates. Adjusted lit for a smaller gap at the top. Created a no switch lid option. attached a copy of the PS mounting STL.
